{
  "text": "In principle a heating curve should be a monotonically increasing curve of temperature vs laser power without singularities. However, one can expect a change in the slope of the curve or a plateau when the sample undergoes a phase transition. An FEA by Montoya and Goncharov (34) has shown that the melting curve should at best show a change of slope, although plateaus have been observed in many experiments. An FEA analysis by Geballe and Jeanloz [CITATION_1] shows that plateaus in heating curves may also result from a change of reflectivity at a transition.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "121030327"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "121030327": {
      "title": "Finite element calculations of the time dependent thermal fluxes in the laser-heated diamond anvil cell",
      "abstract": "The time-dependent temperature distribution in the laser-heated diamond anvil cell (DAC) is examined using finite element simulations. Calculations are carried out for the practically important case of a surface-absorbing metallic plate (coupler) surrounded by a thermally insulating transparent medium. The time scales of the heat transfer in the DAC cavity are found to be typically on the order of tens of microseconds depending on the geometrical and thermochemical parameters of the constituent materials. The use of much shorter laser pulses (e.g., on the order of tens of nanoseconds) creates sharp radial temperature gradients, which result in a very intense and abrupt axial conductive heat transfer that exceeds the radiative heat transfer by several orders of magnitude in the practically usable temperature range (<12 000 K). In contrast, the use of laser pulses with several \u03bcs duration provides sufficiently uniform spatial heating conditions suitable for studying the bulk sample. The effect of the latent..."
    }
  }
}